node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text: We're back with another episode of AD Visits, and today, we're taking you to Hudson Yards to see the home of fashion designer @brian_atwood and husband @drjakedeutsch. With photography on every wall and incredible city views 64 stories above Manhattan, explore their high-rise artistic aerie. Cover photo by @twilliamsphoto.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 05, 2021. May be an image of bedroom.

node.text:
When Jed and @victoriacairo bought a weekend house in the nearby Massachusetts Berkshires, they were newly engaged and pictured a place where friends and family would come for rollicking weekends filled with nature walks, bonfires, and libations. Of course, as the saying goes, you plan and God laughs. First came marriage; then they discovered they had a child on the way—son Otis is now 20 months. Then in March 2020, just as the pandemic was circling overhead, they packed their car for what they imagined would be a week or two of solitude in the country. Fourteen months later, they haven’t left.

See the place they call home at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; styled by @michaelreynoldsnyc; architecture and design by @sachslindores; words by @janekeltnerdev.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 05, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Says @klausbaer of @wrjdesign about this home in Wyoming: “For us, it’s about creating interiors and homes that are in harmony with nature. And how we put those elements together so that the architecture and the interiors are of the place.”

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @ericpiasecki; design by @wrjdesign; architecture by @berlin_architects; words by @jenniferleeflowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 05, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Set your sights high above the Bay of Palma when entering @cap_rocat, a former military fortress dating back to the 19th century. Declared a heritage asset and listed as a national monument, meticulous care was taken to preserve the exceptional architecture of this ancient limestone complex. Maintaining the harmony of Mallorca without disrupting the Spanish island’s biodiversity was also part of the blueprints. This award-winning project by Antonio Obrador’s (@antonioobrador.arquitectos) studio resulted in a uniquely secluded hotel, out of view from the mainland and the sea.

Explore more hotels with breathtaking landscapes at our bio link. Photo courtesy of @cap_rocat; words by @kasiadietz.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 04, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Recalling how he was raised in France, @chefludo says, “the kitchen has its own table, and you have a table for the guests.” Archways visually connect this space to the adjacent kitchen. The Lefebvres typically eat around the @williamssonomahome midcentury-style dining set next to a painting by Ludo titled "d'Yquem" in reference to the prized Château d'Yquem wine labels integrated into the piece. Ludo bought the chandelier from @lawsonfenning, which is near his @petittroisla restaurant on Melrose in Hollywood.

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by @juliesoefer; design by @marieflaniganinteriors; styled by Jessica Holtzman; words by @jessnritz.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 04, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Given its promise of food with a view, family hangouts mostly happen in this Malibu home’s kitchen. A long sight line stretches from the room through the adjacent family area and out to the pool. “This is where we gather after coming home from our disparate lives,” designer Vanessa Alexander (@alexanderdesignbuild) says. The unique slotted skylight echoes the floating stairs in the entry hall.

Step inside the home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @rowelosangeles; design by @alexanderdesignbuild; words by @leilanimarielabong.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 04, 2021. May be an image of furniture, tree and outdoors.

node.text:
“Brian and Tracy’s last house was a Tudor without a lot of sunlight, so the question was ‘How do you bring a bright, contemporary spirit to a house with traditional bones?’ Here, the challenge was flipped—we wanted to bring a sense of warmth and coziness to a pristine contemporary house,” designer @jeremiahbrent says of the L.A. project he designed with husband @nateberkus.

Explore every sunny corner at our bio link. Photo by @trevortondro; styling by @colinking; design by @nateberkus and @jeremiahbrent; architecture by @mccleandesign; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 03, 2021. May be an image of indoor and brick wall.

node.text:
This Finger Lakes home’s wine cellar and cigar room is hidden behind a bookcase that’s also a door. Says designer @thomfilicia, "We wanted to give each room that one moment that is the star of the show. And the wine cellar was a space that was very important to the owner. To have a space that felt like it was his space.”

See the New York retreat at our bio link. Photo by Amy Lamb; design by @thomfilicia; words by @arielfoxman.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 03, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
As people spend more time at home and more money on wellness, the bathroom can become, as #AD100 designer @milesredd puts it, “much more than a spot to brush your teeth.”The primary bath of Ryan Murphy’s (@mrrpmurphy) L.A. pad, designed by #AD100 designer @pamelashamshiri, provides a textbook example, where a hulking Pele de Tigre marble tub by @thehaasbrothers is surrounded by a fleet of Pierre Jeanneret seating. 

Discover how designers are taking bathrooms up a notch — and read more from @archdigestpro — at our bio link. Photo by @dcmphoto.biz; styling by @michaelreynoldsnyc; design by @studioshamshiri; words by @_h_mart_.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 03, 2021. May be an image of table and living room.

node.text:
When invited to take on a demanding project just outside of Paris, interior designers Corinne Sachot and Gabriel Kowalski jumped at the opportunity. “We had a good feeling about them,” Sachot says about the clients. “They are quite spontaneous and enthusiastic. So, we visited the house, which was built in 1968.”

Tour the tranquil home at our bio link. Photo by @matthieusalvaing; words by @gaygassmann.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 02, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
“I like having a small dark entrance that opens to lighter, brighter spaces,” says designer Matthew Bees (@mgmbees) of his Charleston apartment’s foyer. The walls are done in chocolate moiré from @schumacher1889 that have been trimmed in @samuelandsons grosgrain. Bees had the mahogany-stained doors made. They lead to the guest bedroom. “The apartment had heart pine flooring throughout that I had stripped and then whitewashed,” he says. The matching tables on either side of the door are English mahogany demilunes. “I scored them at Clutter consignment in Savannah.”

See more of his nouveau-traditionalist home at our bio link. Photo by @annieschlechter; design by @mgmbees; words by @robertbythebook.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 02, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
#AD100 designer @kenfulk’s highly sophisticated interiors—often swathed in colorful hand-painted wallpaper and decorated with a mix of centuries-old antiques and custom contemporary pieces—are almost instantly recognizable to anyone with an appreciation for design. “I do strive hard not to have a signature look, but there is an obvious DNA to the things that we create that makes the spaces easily identifiable.” His most recent endeavor that serves as a shining example of his design philosophy? @thequinhouseboston, a members-only social club that opened this summer in Boston’s famous Back Bay neighborhood.

Step inside at our bio link. Photo by @jennapeffley; design by @kenfulk; words by Jessica Cherner.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 01, 2021. May be an image of furniture and kitchen.

node.text:
As part of their vision to reimagine this classic log cabin in Wyoming, @rushjenkins and @klausbaer of @wrjdesign brought the palette of the sky, mountains, and landscape into the warm-hued interiors. Metallic details—the handiwork of local craftspeople—can be found everywhere: In the iron accents of a coffee table, brass-and-bronze chandelier in the kitchen, and striking lattice-fronted bar.

Tour the rustic home at our bio link. Photo by @ericpiasecki; design by @wrjdesign; architecture by @berlin_architects; words by @jenniferleeflowers.
